            , <rs id="t17790519-23-cd133" type="crimeDate">May 18th</rs>
                  <join result="offenceCrimeDate" targOrder="Y" targets="t17790519-23-off132 t17790519-23-cd133"></join>.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17790519-23-person257">
                  ISAAC
                   SCOTT
               <interp inst="t17790519-23-person257" type="surname" value="SCOTT"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17790519-23-person257" type="given" value="ISAAC"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17790519-23-person257" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             sworn.</p>
               <p>I am a <rs id="t17790519-23-viclabel134" type="occupation">linen-draper</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t17790519-23-victim256 t17790519-23-viclabel134"></join>. The prisoners came into my shop to be served with some linen. My servant shewed them several pieces; I was in the shop when they came in, but went up stairs. I was called down and told they had taken a piece of linen. I went and found them at the Coach and Horses, and brought them back, and the servant at the ale-house brought the linen in after them.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17790519-23-person258">
                  ALEXANDER
                   YOUNG
               <interp inst="t17790519-23-person258" type="surname" value="YOUNG"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17790519-23-person258" type="given" value="ALEXANDER"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17790519-23-person258" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             sworn.</p>
               <p>On Tuesday the 18th of March, at about half after six o'clock, I went to Mr. Scott's to fetch a piece of cloth for my mother; the prisoners were in the shop, one of them had a red cloak on; I saw a piece of cloth hang down under the red cloak; I saw it move just before she lifted it up under her cloak. I had a suspicion of them. When they were gone, I told Mr. Scott of it, and I staid till they were brought back again.</p>
               <p>Which had the red cloak on? - 
               <persName id="t17790519-23-person259">
                  Sarah
                   Armstrong
               <interp inst="t17790519-23-person259" type="surname" value="Armstrong"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17790519-23-person259" type="given" value="Sarah"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17790519-23-person259" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            ; the other was at the other end of the counter.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17790519-23-person260">
                  ESTHER
                   SAVOY
               <interp inst="t17790519-23-person260" type="surname" value="SAVOY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17790519-23-person260" type="given" value="ESTHER"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17790519-23-person260" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
             sworn.</p>
               <p>I am servant at the Coach and Horses, in Bartholomew Close. I was coming out of the yard; the prisoners were in the house. Hickman asked me to bring up a bundle she had dropped down the cellar stairs; I went to fetch the bundle; before I returned, Mr. Scott came, and took them out of the house. I carried the linen to Mr. Scott's.</p>
               <p>Where was Hickman when she asked you to bring up the bundle? - Sitting on our stairs next to the cellar stairs; I delivered the linen to Mr. Scott.</p>
               <p>Mr. Scott. I took care of the linen till we went to Guildhall then I delivered it to the constable.</p>
               <p>(
               <persName id="t17790519-23-person261">
                  Joseph
                   Spencer
               <interp inst="t17790519-23-person261" type="surname" value="Spencer"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17790519-23-person261" type="given" value="Joseph"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17790519-23-person261" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             a constable produced the linen which was deposed to by the prosecutor.</p>
               <p>HICKMAN's DEFENCE.</p>
               <p>I leave it to your generosity; that boy and woman are bribed to take our lives away.</p>
               <p>ARMSTRONG's DEFENCE.</p>
               <p>The woman told the boy they should go to the Old Bailey, and have some money, and laughed as she has done now in your lordship's face.</p>
               <p>BOTH <rs id="t17790519-23-verdict135" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t17790519-23-verdict135" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
               GUILTY
            </rs>.</p>
               <p>Tried by the London Jury before Mr. RECORDER.</p>
